00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:34.420
that we use our imagination.

00:32:34.420 --> 00:32:42.250
When I was on Capitol
Hill, I worked on a law

00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:45.160
to get the foreign bank account
question on the tax return.

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:49.430
That's the question Paul
Manafort answered dishonestly.

00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:51.680
But there's a great
story behind it

00:32:51.680 --> 00:32:54.600
and it involves wealthy
business people.

00:32:54.600 --> 00:32:57.880
It involves the Chicago
mob, the Cleveland mob,

00:32:57.880 --> 00:33:02.820
equal opportunity prostitutes,
one's Caucasian, one's Latin.

00:33:02.820 --> 00:33:06.230
But there's a lot of impediments
to my writing that book.

00:33:06.230 --> 00:33:12.640
First of all, my writing is all
legal briefs and I can't write,

00:33:12.640 --> 00:33:14.750
I can't write dialogue.

00:33:14.750 --> 00:33:16.500
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan:
Let me ask you about this.

00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:20.550
So you're writing a book about
your experiences on Capitol Hill

00:33:20.550 --> 00:33:24.800
with the really complicated
world of banking and finances

00:33:24.800 --> 00:33:27.720
and that's -- You have
a very special thing

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:30.540
and I promise I'll
get to your question.

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:32.340
We all have a very
special thing.

00:33:32.340 --> 00:33:34.550
Any of us who wants to write
a book or even who thinks

00:33:34.550 --> 00:33:38.180
about that a little bit in
their head, you know something

00:33:38.180 --> 00:33:39.500
that nobody else knows.

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:42.930
You know things that are special
and you have to ask yourself,

00:33:42.930 --> 00:33:45.680
and I ask myself this
every day as I'm writing.

00:33:45.680 --> 00:33:47.490
Why do I care about this?

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:50.390
Why do I care about this
because if I don't care,

00:33:50.390 --> 00:33:51.840
the reader won't care.

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:53.690
How do I make the reader care?

00:33:53.690 --> 00:33:56.320
So if I had to give
you advice about how

00:33:56.320 --> 00:33:57.960
to write a complicated
book and you say, oh,

00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:00.110
I can't write dialogue and I
don't know how to, you know,

00:34:00.110 --> 00:34:03.200
it's a very complicated topic,
I say yeah, isn't that great?

00:34:03.200 --> 00:34:07.840
Sit down at your computer
and type chapter one

00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:11.000
and see what story
you're telling.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:14.280
And at every moment ask
yourself why is this important,

00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:16.220
what difference does it make

00:34:16.220 --> 00:34:20.190
and how can I advance the
story and what is my goal.

00:34:20.190 --> 00:34:22.660
Don't worry about -- I
mean, it's interesting

00:34:22.660 --> 00:34:25.880
because the idea of writing a
novel is incredibly daunting.

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:27.570
You know, you sit at your
computer and you think,

00:34:27.570 --> 00:34:29.750
I have to write a novel.

00:34:29.750 --> 00:34:31.370
This is impossible.

00:34:31.370 --> 00:34:32.920
But you're writing a page.

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:34.620
You're writing a paragraph.

00:34:34.620 --> 00:34:35.920
Just try that.

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:39.300
Tell yourself I'm just
going to write one paragraph

00:34:39.300 --> 00:34:40.780
and then I'm going to get up.

00:34:40.780 --> 00:34:42.590
See if you can do that
and I bet you can.

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:46.030
And after you write that one
paragraph, write another one.

00:34:46.030 --> 00:34:48.130
And then when you get
your first draft done,

00:34:48.130 --> 00:34:50.110
worry about making the
dialogue better and worry

00:34:50.110 --> 00:34:52.840
about the plot holes
and worry about all that

00:34:52.840 --> 00:34:56.790
but you can't write a book
by just thinking about it.

00:34:56.790 --> 00:34:59.230
Dennis Lehane always
talks, says that he thinks

00:34:59.230 --> 00:35:00.970
about writing his novel so much

00:35:00.970 --> 00:35:04.130
that when he comes home he can't
understand why the manuscript

00:35:04.130 --> 00:35:08.520
isn't longer because it feels
like he's been working on it.

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:09.820
So that's what I would say.

00:35:09.820 --> 00:35:11.120
&gt;&gt; Is it possible to work

00:35:11.120 --> 00:35:14.270
with an author that's
a published author

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:16.540
that can make this
into a real story?

00:35:16.540 --> 00:35:17.840
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan:
Is it possible to work

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:20.330
with a published author that
could make it into a story?

00:35:20.330 --> 00:35:22.540
Is just a casual question?

00:35:22.540 --> 00:35:26.990
We'll talk afterwards.

00:35:26.990 --> 00:35:30.270
Only you can write the
story that you can write.

00:35:30.270 --> 00:35:34.480
There are writing teachers and
there are editors and we'll talk

00:35:34.480 --> 00:35:35.950
after this program is over.

00:35:35.950 --> 00:35:37.250
Sounds like a good book.

00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:38.550
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:35:38.550 --> 00:35:39.860
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan: See, you
know, there's always something.

00:35:39.860 --> 00:35:41.160
Yes?

00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:44.480
&gt;&gt; Hello. I'm a college student
