00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:30.280
and so there are
times in my books,

00:38:30.280 --> 00:38:32.000
which are somewhat
legal oriented,

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:35.750
they're not legal thrillers
but they live in that world,

00:38:35.750 --> 00:38:38.310
where there's a legal
question that I have.

00:38:38.310 --> 00:38:41.260
And for some reason, I always
come up with this question

00:38:41.260 --> 00:38:43.640
that I need to know
what the prosecutor say

00:38:43.640 --> 00:38:45.120
or what would the
rule be about this

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:46.600
or how could a judge do that.

00:38:46.600 --> 00:38:49.190
It always sort of happens
about 3 in the afternoon,

00:38:49.190 --> 00:38:51.750
that's sort of the writing
cycle, so I call my husband

00:38:51.750 --> 00:38:54.110
at the office and I
say, hi, sweetheart.

00:38:54.110 --> 00:38:57.100
It's me with a legal
question of the day.

00:38:57.100 --> 00:39:00.180
And then -- And so it's really
great to be living with a lawyer

00:39:00.180 --> 00:39:02.110
to have my own in-house counsel.

00:39:02.110 --> 00:39:04.220
That's really helpful.

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:07.090
But the prosecutor or defense
attorney, my new novel,

00:39:07.090 --> 00:39:11.160
which I guess I can tell you
the name of, which I sent,

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:13.830
I hit send yesterday on it.

00:39:13.830 --> 00:39:17.840
Can you believe [applause],
which was pretty great,

00:39:17.840 --> 00:39:22.540
at 11:58 PM because it was due,
you know it was due by midnight.

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:26.750
It's called "The
Murder List" and it is

00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:31.110
about a young law student who
was caught between her husband,

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:34.550
a defense attorney, and
her boss, a prosecutor.

00:39:34.550 --> 00:39:37.950
So you'll have to read that book
to find out which is better.

00:39:37.950 --> 00:39:44.500
Law is all about knowing the
rules and which side you choose,

00:39:44.500 --> 00:39:47.370
both sides think they're
the side of justice.

00:39:47.370 --> 00:39:49.170
So it just depends
on how you think.

00:39:49.170 --> 00:39:51.210
We have a couple minutes.

00:39:51.210 --> 00:39:52.510
Yes?

00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:57.940
&gt;&gt; Hi. What would you -- What
would be your advice to me,

00:39:57.940 --> 00:40:01.300
I have someone very close me
who's writing a science fiction

00:40:01.300 --> 00:40:05.280
book and has asked me
to read it, edit it,

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:09.970
give me your opinion, and
I just hate it [laughter].

00:40:11.670 --> 00:40:12.970
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi
Ryan: Oh, yeah!

00:40:12.970 --> 00:40:15.250
Welcome to the world of having
a friend who's a writer.

00:40:15.250 --> 00:40:17.940
You're asking -- You have
a friend who wrote a book

00:40:17.940 --> 00:40:19.240
and you just really
don't like it.

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:20.610
Is she or he here?

00:40:20.610 --> 00:40:24.300
&gt;&gt; No. Might watch C-SPAN.

00:40:24.300 --> 00:40:26.460
I don't know.

00:40:26.460 --> 00:40:27.760
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan: Okay.

00:40:27.760 --> 00:40:33.420
So there is always something
good to be said about a book,

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:37.450
even if it is "what a
great idea that is."

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:39.020
You don't have to
finish with, wow,

00:40:39.020 --> 00:40:44.310
but you really didn't do
a very good job with that.

00:40:44.310 --> 00:40:46.680
You can tell what
you really think,

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:49.210
I didn't understand this part,
I didn't understand that part,

00:40:49.210 --> 00:40:51.170
but, wow, what a good idea.

00:40:51.170 --> 00:40:54.840
You're going to -- You
know, when you read reviews

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:58.380
and somebody says five stars
and somebody says one star

00:40:58.380 --> 00:41:00.390
and it's the same
book, you know,

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:01.960
you realize that there's room

00:41:01.960 --> 00:41:04.010
for many different
opinions in the world.

00:41:04.010 --> 00:41:06.880
And some -- You know, my husband
and I can read the same book

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:08.900
and I love it and
he doesn't love it.

00:41:08.900 --> 00:41:10.850
So it's okay not to like it.

00:41:10.850 --> 00:41:14.080
And she or he is your friend,
tell them something good

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:15.660
about the book and point them

00:41:15.660 --> 00:41:17.250
with some constructive
criticism,

00:41:17.250 --> 00:41:20.500
perhaps about what you
thought could be better,

00:41:20.500 --> 00:41:24.190
like I didn't really know
where this was taking place,

00:41:24.190 --> 00:41:27.290
that would be a good thing.

00:41:27.290 --> 00:41:31.250
So it's a dilemma and you're a
good pal for caring about it.

00:41:31.250 --> 00:41:32.980
Thank you very good question.

00:41:32.980 --> 00:41:34.280
Last question.

00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:36.160
We have like a minute,
I think, two?

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:37.460
Two minutes.

00:41:37.460 --> 00:41:39.190
So you get to have some of it.

00:41:39.190 --> 00:41:40.490
&gt;&gt; Sorry. I'm really nervous.

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:42.010
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan:
No, don't be nervous.

00:41:42.010 --> 00:41:46.040
&gt;&gt; I have a couple novels
that I'm trying to finish

00:41:46.040 --> 00:41:48.770
because I can never seem
to let the characters go.

00:41:48.770 --> 00:41:50.860
How do you know when
to end a novel?

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:52.530
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan: How do
you know when to end a novel?

00:41:52.530 --> 00:41:54.360
She's saying that she's
written a couple of novels

00:41:54.360 --> 00:41:56.610
and she can never let
the characters go.

00:41:56.610 --> 00:42:01.550
I know exactly when I'm finished

00:42:01.550 --> 00:42:04.920
and that is kind
of a magical thing.

00:42:04.920 --> 00:42:07.720
You know how you revise
and you revise and revise

00:42:07.720 --> 00:42:11.180
and you're looking
at every word,

00:42:11.180 --> 00:42:13.080
and I do that so passionately

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:16.210
because revision
is the ballgame.

00:42:16.210 --> 00:42:18.460
Every first draft is terrible.

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:21.470
And then you work on it and work
on it and work on it and try

00:42:21.470 --> 00:42:24.240
to find the book in there
that you are really writing.

00:42:24.240 --> 00:42:27.850
And I remember with
"Trust Me" it happened.

00:42:27.850 --> 00:42:32.820
I was doing a revision and I
was reading along and I forgot

00:42:32.820 --> 00:42:34.710
that I wrote the book.

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:38.290
I realized that I was
just reading this story

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:40.640
and not trying to fix it anymore

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:43.380
and that's how I
knew it was done.

00:42:43.380 --> 00:42:46.140
You're telling a story with
a beginning, middle and end.

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:47.440
Is it good?

00:42:47.440 --> 00:42:48.740
Is it compelling?

00:42:48.740 --> 00:42:50.040
When you read it,
do you love it?

00:42:50.040 --> 00:42:52.040
If you love it , then your
readers will love it too.

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:54.600
And then just stop and
put it out in the world.

00:42:54.600 --> 00:42:58.120
Don't keep that book a secret.

00:42:58.120 --> 00:43:00.640
Share that and let
your book live.

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:02.800
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:04.100
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi
Ryan: Of course.

00:43:04.100 --> 00:43:06.070
Last question, real fast.

00:43:06.070 --> 00:43:07.510
&gt;&gt; You're a journalist.

00:43:07.510 --> 00:43:10.510
I'm a producer in TV news.

00:43:10.510 --> 00:43:13.850
You're looking for the
truth in your journalism,

00:43:13.850 --> 00:43:17.630
how do not get bogged down
in trying to respect facts

00:43:17.630 --> 00:43:20.310
and the truth when you're
writing something that's not

00:43:20.310 --> 00:43:21.730
true, a fiction?

00:43:21.730 --> 00:43:25.860
How do you not get bogged down
in trying to respect one part

00:43:25.860 --> 00:43:28.010
of you and working
on the other part?

00:43:28.010 --> 00:43:29.310
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan:
How do I get bogged

00:43:29.310 --> 00:43:30.610
down in writing fiction --

00:43:30.610 --> 00:43:31.910
&gt;&gt; Not get bogged down.

00:43:31.910 --> 00:43:33.210
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan:
Not get bogged down?

00:43:33.210 --> 00:43:34.510
How do I get bogged down,
I can really tell you that.

00:43:34.510 --> 00:43:36.900
How do I not get bogged
down in the facts?

00:43:36.900 --> 00:43:39.840
&gt;&gt; Yeah and trying to respect
the facts in your research

00:43:39.840 --> 00:43:41.290
when you're writing fiction.

00:43:41.290 --> 00:43:43.210
&gt;&gt; Hank Phillippi Ryan:
You know, when I research,

00:43:43.210 --> 00:43:47.150
I put it all in my head and
then I just don't ever look

00:43:47.150 --> 00:43:48.970
at the research notebooks again.

00:43:48.970 --> 00:43:52.290
I just sort of consume this
information and put myself

00:43:52.290 --> 00:43:56.050
in a place that I want the book
to be and then I just write it.

00:43:56.050 --> 00:44:00.790
So fiction is different, so
different from doing journalism.

00:44:00.790 --> 00:44:03.490
So I try to just relax
and let the book come

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:06.240
out the best way that it can be.

00:44:06.240 --> 00:44:10.480
It's fun. My job is to take
a really complicated bunch

00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:14.090
of stuff and make it
into a fascinating story

00:44:14.090 --> 00:44:16.710
and that's what I
try to do every day.

00:44:16.710 --> 00:44:18.290
I am getting the wrap-up sign.

00:44:18.290 --> 00:44:19.590
Thank you so much.

00:44:19.590 --> 00:44:21.540
Let me just say, remember
the last time you went

00:44:21.540 --> 00:44:27.550
to the library and you pulled
out a book and you looked at it.

00:44:27.550 --> 00:44:30.380
Think about the author
when you do that.

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:34.230
When you go to a library and
select a book and take it home

00:44:34.230 --> 00:44:38.100
with you, you have
made an author happy

00:44:38.100 --> 00:44:40.870
and I'm very grateful to
be part of that world.

00:44:40.870 --> 00:44:47.250
Thank you so much for coming
here today [applause].

